This is exactly why the change shouldn't be made on the shared contact point. Two separate problems, two fixes:

**1. Don't touch the email path — make this additive**

If you replace the message template on a topic that email subscribers use, they'll start receiving raw JSON. Instead, keep the existing SNS integration (with Grafana's default readable message) exactly as it is, and add a second delivery path just for the machine pipeline:

- A Grafana contact point can hold multiple integrations. Add a second AWS SNS integration to the same contact point, pointing to a **new** topic that only the SQS queue subscribes to. That integration gets the JSON template.
- Or create a separate contact point and route alerts to both via notification policies with "continue matching" enabled.

Either way, emails keep looking exactly like today, and the Lambda gets clean JSON. Nobody loses information.

**2. Alerts without labels: use a generic template + Lambda defaults**

Don't hard-code six labels that 260 rules don't have. Dump whatever labels and annotations each alert actually has:

```
{
  "alerts": [
    {{- range $i, $alert := .Alerts }}
    {{- if $i }},{{ end }}
    {
      "status": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Status }},
      "labels": {
        {{- range $j, $p := $alert.Labels.SortedPairs }}
        {{- if $j }},{{ end }}
        {{ printf "%q" $p.Name }}: {{ printf "%q" $p.Value }}
        {{- end }}
      },
      "annotations": {
        {{- range $j, $p := $alert.Annotations.SortedPairs }}
        {{- if $j }},{{ end }}
        {{ printf "%q" $p.Name }}: {{ printf "%q" $p.Value }}
        {{- end }}
      }
    }
    {{- end }}
  ]
}
```

Every Grafana alert automatically carries at least `alertname` and `grafana_folder` labels, and most rules have summary/description annotations — so even label-less alerts arrive with a usable identity. The Lambda then fills gaps: if `component` or `stage` is missing, apply defaults or a small lookup table keyed on alertname/folder. Teams can then add proper labels rule-by-rule over time instead of a big-bang migration of 260 alerts.

